"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443743","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-14","<p>Consistent with all official events, the Chancellor was supported by a small number of officials from his private office and the Treasury press office when speaking at the St David’s hotel and at the two associated visits.</p><br /><p>Costs associated with the major economy speech at the St David’s hotel in Cardiff were met within the existing events budget at HM Treasury. Invitations were not issued by the department.</p><br /><p>The event at the Salt Bar was not a Government event and so no costs were met by the Treasury and no civil servants attended.</p><br /> <br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","21923 ; 21924 ; 21926","2016-01-14T16:12:02.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443743/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443743/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-11","Treasury: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether invitations to the event at which he spoke on 7 January 2016 at St David's Hotel were issued by his Department.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","21925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443744","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-14","<p>Consistent with all official events, the Chancellor was supported by a small number of officials from his private office and the Treasury press office when speaking at the St David’s hotel and at the two associated visits.</p><br /><p>Costs associated with the major economy speech at the St David’s hotel in Cardiff were met within the existing events budget at HM Treasury. Invitations were not issued by the department.</p><br /><p>The event at the Salt Bar was not a Government event and so no costs were met by the Treasury and no civil servants attended.</p><br /> <br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","21923 ; 21924 ; 21925","2016-01-14T16:12:03.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443744/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443744/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-11","Treasury: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many civil servants accompanied him on his visit to Cardiff on 7 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","21926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443745","Department for Education","false","2016-01-18","<p>Ensuring that young people leaving care are able to access suitable accommodation is a priority for this Government. In 2015, 92% of care leavers aged 19-21 were in suitable accommodation. We have introduced measures to help ensure care leavers have access to suitable accommodation but we are determined to do more.</p><br /><p>That is why, during the last Parliament, we introduced the ‘Staying Put’ duty, which requires local authorities to support young people to continue living with their former foster carers up to age 21.</p><br /><p>Statutory guidance sets out the factors that local authorities must take into account when determining the suitability of accommodation for their children and young people. The guidance was strengthened in 2015 to make clear that bed and breakfast accommodation should only be used in exceptional circumstances and for no longer than 2 working days. Since 2014, Ofsted inspections have assessed whether local authorities are ensuring that care leavers have access to suitable accommodation.</p><br /><p>Further measures to support care leavers to access suitable accommodation will be considered as part of the refreshed cross-Government care leaver strategy, to be launched later this year.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-01-18T15:41:29.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443745/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443745/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-11","Care Leavers: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to reduce the number of former care leavers living in unsuitable accommodation.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","21845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443746","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<br /><p>There are 12 Defence press and public relations posts based in Scotland, all of which have duties relating to Scotland.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Royal Navy</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Army</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Air Force</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Defence press and public relations personnel provide a UK-wide service and therefore would deal with matters relating to Scotland when required.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-01-14T16:12:36.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443746/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443746/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-11","Ministry of Defence: Information Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 7 January 2016 to Question 20602, how many of the 183 Ministry of Defence public relations staff referred to are (a) based in Scotland, (b) have duties relating to Scotland.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","21964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443747","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>The UK has made its assessment of the implications of low speed ejection. A temporary weight restriction has been imposed for UK pilots, which does not constrain flight operations at this time. A range of design solutions are being developed and these are expected to be in place before the aircraft enters service in the UK.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-01-14T17:08:07.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443747/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443747/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-11","Air Force: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he has made an assessment for the implications for his policy of the merits decision by the US Air Force to extend weight restrictions of F-35 Lightning II pilots until 2018; and whether his Department has issued similar guidelines for UK pilots.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","22003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443748","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-19","<p>The purpose of my visit to the USS Ronald Reagan was to share US thinking about security challenges in North and Southeast Asia. I was accompanied by the Vice Chief of the Defence Staff, the Director General for Security Policy, the UK Ambassador and the Defence Attache.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-01-19T15:34:02.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443748/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443748/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-11","USS Ronald Reagan: Official Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the purpose was of the visit of his officials to the USS Ronald Reagan on 8 January 2016; and what the rank of the visiting officials was.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","21988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443749","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-15","<p>40 personnel from 40 Commando Royal Marines took part in Exercise PLATINUM LION during July 2015. This was primarily an infantry skills exercise with no major assets deployed.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-15T13:33:40.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443749/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443749/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-11","Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) assets and (b) personnel of his Department took part in Exercise Platinum Lion in collaboration with the US, Romanian and Bulgarian armed forces.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","22000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443750","Department for Education","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Government believes that all children should have the opportunity to receive a high quality and appropriate sex and relationship education (SRE).</p><p>SRE is compulsory in maintained secondary schools. Primary schools can choose to teach SRE in an age-appropriate way. All schools providing SRE, including academies and primary schools, must have regard to the Secretary of State’s Sex and Relationship Education Guidance (2000).</p><p>While the Secretary of State regularly discusses such matters with her colleagues, there have been no formal meetings recently about improving the quality of sex and relationship education in schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-14T14:56:38.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443750/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443750/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-11","Sex and Relationship Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with her ministerial colleagues on improving the quality of sex and relationship education in schools.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","21877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443751","Women and Equalities","false","2016-01-14","<p>Since 2013, officials in the Government Equalities Office have been working with the Home Office and police representatives on how best to use provisions within the Equality Act 2010 to help increase the number of BME police officers.</p><p>The officer workforce is more representative in terms of gender and ethnicity than it has ever been. At 31 March 2015, there were 6,979 BME officers representing 5.5% of all police officers (compared with 4.6% in 2010, 3.6% in 2006 and only 2.2% in 2000).</p><p>At 31 March 2015, there were 35,738 female officers, representing 28.2% of all police officers (compared with 25.7% in 2010, and only 16.5% in 2000).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-01-14T14:44:11.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443751/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443751/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-01-11","Police: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what recent discussions she has had with her ministerial colleagues on increasing the number of BME police officers.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","21879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443752","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-19","<p>Following public consultation, the government introduced fees in Employment Tribunals as a way of reducing the burden on the taxpayer and to encourage parties to seek alternative ways of resolving their disputes.</p><p>In June of last year we announced the start of the post-implementation review of the introduction of fees in the Employment Tribunals. This review will consider, so far as is possible, the impact the fees have had on those with protected characteristics and the types of case they bring.</p><p>The review will report in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-01-19T10:29:05.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443752/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443752/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of employment tribunal fees on the ability of individuals to bring forward discrimination claims.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","21876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443753","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-18","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","21794","2016-01-18T11:42:09.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443753/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443753/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-11","Carer's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many carers were (a) in receipt of and (b) have an underlying entitlement to carer's allowance as a result of caring for someone who is in receipt of (i) attendance allowance, (ii) personal independence payment and (iii) disability living allowance.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","21795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443754","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-18","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","21795","2016-01-18T11:42:09.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443754/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443754/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-11","Carer's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many recipients of carer's allowance were in receipt of (a) attendance allowance and (b) personal independence payment in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","21794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443755","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-14","<p>The report needs to be considered by law enforcement agencies and the government before it can be published. This includes considering whether redactions need to be made. Lady Justice Macur has recommended that certain material should be considered for redaction.</p><br /><p>The work is proceeding at pace with a view to publication as soon as possible.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","21818 ; 21820","2016-01-14T13:01:27.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443755/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443755/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Child Abuse in North Wales Judicial Inquiry Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2015 to Question 19906, by whom Lady Justice Macur's report is being considered.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","21819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443756","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-14","<p>The report needs to be considered by law enforcement agencies and the government before it can be published. This includes considering whether redactions need to be made. Lady Justice Macur has recommended that certain material should be considered for redaction.</p><br /><p>The work is proceeding at pace with a view to publication as soon as possible.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","21818 ; 21819","2016-01-14T13:01:27.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443756/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443756/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Child Abuse in North Wales Judicial Inquiry Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2015 to Question 19906, when he expects to publish Lady Justice Macur's report.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","21820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443757","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-14","<p>The report needs to be considered by law enforcement agencies and the government before it can be published. This includes considering whether redactions need to be made. Lady Justice Macur has recommended that certain material should be considered for redaction.</p><br /><p>The work is proceeding at pace with a view to publication as soon as possible.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","21819 ; 21820","2016-01-14T13:01:27.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443757/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443757/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Child Abuse in North Wales Judicial Inquiry Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2015 to Question 19906, for what reasons the Government is considering the report of Lady Justice Macur prior to its publication.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","21818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443758","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-15","<p>The recipients of expenditure on broadcasting and media bodies in 2015 were: Ofcom; BFI; S4C; and the National Film and Television School.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-15T11:32:53.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443758/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443758/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-11","Mass Media: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 53 of the Statement of Funding Policy 2015, who the recipients of expenditure on broadcasting and media bodies were in 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","21973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443759","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-14","<p>We have a long and shared history with Bahrain. Our relationship with Bahrain is important for our respective security and prosperity. We will continue to work with Bahrain to support their reform agenda. Bahrain has made progress but we are clear more needs to be done.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-14T17:35:28.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443759/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443759/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-11","Bahrain: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department has an official statement of the UK's relationship with Bahrain and the Bahraini government.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","21768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443760","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-14","<p>We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain - including at the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group meeting which was most recently held in November 2015. The UK continues to encourage the Government of Bahrain to meet its human rights obligations, including the treatment of detainees in detention, and to honour all conventions to which it is a party. We are aware of the case of Hassan Mushaima and have raised it with the Government of Bahrain.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-14T17:28:13.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443760/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443760/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-11","Bahrain: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the government of Bahrain on (a) the treatment of opposition leaders in that country and (b) medical facilities available to Hassan Mushaima.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","21958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443761","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-14","<p>We engage with a broad range of political groups in Bahrain to encourage their participation in inclusive political dialogue. I had the opportunity to do so during my recent visit to Bahrain in June 2015.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-14T17:32:53.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443761/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443761/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-11","Bahrain: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with opposition politicians and groups in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","21959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443762","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-14","<p>Major transport schemes which are subject to ministerial approval include a value for money assessment in which benefits and costs are assessed. Since 2011 – the first year for which data is readily available – the Department has given final funding approval and awarded a grant to one major transport schemes whose costs exceeded its benefits:</p><br /><p>- Sheffield Tram Train Pilot. Approval of this scheme was granted on the basis that it is a pilot designed to test the range of issues, costs and opportunities involved in introducing the tram train concept to the UK.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-14T15:35:21.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443762/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443762/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-11","Department for Transport: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many grants his Department awarded to projects for which the range of values in the Department's benefit-cost ratio assessment included negative values in each of the last six years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","21766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443763","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-19","<p>We will be working closely over the coming months with the five cities in which Clean Air Zones are to be introduced to develop the detail of the actions required. An impact assessment of the proposals for Clean Air Zones will be published later this year alongside a consultation on a framework for Clean Air Zones and the secondary legislation to be introduced.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","21785","2016-01-19T11:14:33.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443763/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443763/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-11","Clean Air Zones: Impact Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when her Department plans to publish a full impact assessment of the Government's proposal for clean air zones.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","21782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443764","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-19","<p>Local Authorities already have powers under Part 3 of the Transport Act 2000 which can be used to establish Clean Air Zones. Vehicles have to comply with European emissions standards in order to be put on the market and we have been pushing strongly for action to improve the standards and for real driving emission testing to be introduced as quickly as possible.</p><br /><p>As set out in our air quality plan for reducing nitrogen dioxide emissions, published on 17 December 2015, we will be requiring five cities in England to introduce Clean Air Zones and discourage certain types of vehicles from entering them. The plan identifies different categories of Clean Air Zone which may be appropriate depending on the circumstances of a particular Local Authority introducing a zone. However, the plan explains that, for those five cities, we have assessed that we can bring the UK into compliance with nitrogen dioxide limits without requiring the Local Authorities to impose restrictions on passenger cars. Further, the plan sets out the Mayor of London’s commitment to introduce an Ultra Low Emission Zone by September 2020 covering a range of vehicles, including passenger cars.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","21784","2016-01-19T11:23:25.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443764/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443764/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-11","Clean Air Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, for what reason passenger cars have been exempted from the proposed clean air zones in her Department's plan to reduce nitrogen dioxide emissions.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","21783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443765","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-19","<p>Local Authorities already have powers under Part 3 of the Transport Act 2000 which can be used to establish Clean Air Zones. Vehicles have to comply with European emissions standards in order to be put on the market and we have been pushing strongly for action to improve the standards and for real driving emission testing to be introduced as quickly as possible.</p><br /><p>As set out in our air quality plan for reducing nitrogen dioxide emissions, published on 17 December 2015, we will be requiring five cities in England to introduce Clean Air Zones and discourage certain types of vehicles from entering them. The plan identifies different categories of Clean Air Zone which may be appropriate depending on the circumstances of a particular Local Authority introducing a zone. However, the plan explains that, for those five cities, we have assessed that we can bring the UK into compliance with nitrogen dioxide limits without requiring the Local Authorities to impose restrictions on passenger cars. Further, the plan sets out the Mayor of London’s commitment to introduce an Ultra Low Emission Zone by September 2020 covering a range of vehicles, including passenger cars.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","21783","2016-01-19T11:23:25.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443765/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443765/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-11","Clean Air Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to empower local authorities in proposed clean air zones to charge private cars which do not comply with EU vehicle emission standards.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","21784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443766","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-19","<p>We will be working closely over the coming months with the five cities in which Clean Air Zones are to be introduced to develop the detail of the actions required. An impact assessment of the proposals for Clean Air Zones will be published later this year alongside a consultation on a framework for Clean Air Zones and the secondary legislation to be introduced.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","21782","2016-01-19T11:14:33.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443766/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443766/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-11","Clean Air Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to announce details of the responsibilities to be imposed on the five cities in which clean air zones will be introduced.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","21785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443767","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-18","<p>We assess emissions in terms of nitrogen oxides (NO<sub>x</sub>) rather than nitrogen dioxide (NO<sub>2</sub>) because the proportion of NO<sub>2</sub> varies significantly across vehicle types. Passenger cars (including both petrol and diesel vehicles) contribute 29% of the total emissions of NO<sub>x</sub> in the UK. Passenger cars contribute 45% of NO<sub>X</sub> emissions from road transport.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-18T14:40:06.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443767/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443767/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-11","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of nitrogen dioxide pollution in the UK is caused by emissions from private cars.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","21781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443768","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-01-14","<p>The funding of Hinkley Point C is a commercial matter for the parties involved. However, the agreements between EDF and CGN announced in October 2015 show the commitment of all sides to the project. EDF and CGN have confirmed major investment in Hinkley Point C and are working to rapidly conclude the detailed investment documentation.</p><br /><p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State expects to be in a position to take her final decision on the Contract for Difference and associated agreements for Hinkley Point C once the documentation relating to equity investment into the project is finalised.</p><br /> <br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-01-14T15:02:53.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443768/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443768/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-11","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what contingency plans her Department has put in place in the event of one or more stakeholders in the Hinkley Point C project being unable to raise sufficient funding to complete development.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","21904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443769","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-25","<p><strong></strong></p><p>We have ongoing discussions with the construction sector about the CITB Levy scheme on how existing arrangements are affected, and whether any changes are required, including whether they may wish to see changes to the CITB levy regime when the apprenticeship levy takes effect.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-25T16:32:50.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443769/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443769/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-11","Construction: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had with representatives of the construction industry who already pay into the Construction Industry Training Board Levy scheme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","21833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443770","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-25","<p>The apprenticeship levy is economy wide. It will apply to all employers with a pay bill over £3,000,000 including those in the construction and engineering construction sectors.We are aware that the industry is concerned about the potential impact of paying two levies. We are working closely with the Industry Training Boards who will consult with their members ahead of the introduction of the apprenticeships levy on how their existing arrangements will be affected.</p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-25T16:29:13.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443770/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443770/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-11","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to ensure that businesses which contribute to the Construction Industry Training Board Levy scheme do not also pay the apprenticeship levy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","21834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443771","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-19","<br /><p>Every death in custody is a tragedy and we are committed to reducing the number of deaths in prisons.</p><br /><p>Summary statistics on deaths in prison custody by apparent cause are published quarterly, and the latest annual figures, for the ten years to September 2015, can be found in Table 2 of the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/472712/Safety-in-custody-summary-q2-2015.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/472712/Safety-in-custody-summary-q2-2015.xls</a></p><br /> <br /><p>Figures on the number of deaths caused by the use of “legal highs”, or new psychoactive substances, are not held centrally. All deaths in prison custody are subject to a coroner’s inquest, and it is the responsibility of the coroner to determine the cause of death. The NOMS system for classifying deaths provides a provisional classification for administrative and statistical purposes. The final classifications are determined at inquest.</p><br /> <br />","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-19T17:56:17.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443771/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443771/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many deaths in prison were caused by the use of legal highs in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","21829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443772","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-15","<p>We do not tolerate violence of any kind in prison and any assault is treated extremely seriously. Any prisoner who commits an act of violence can expect to have action taken against them.</p><p>Statistics for assaults on staff are published in the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin.</p><p>The information requested may be found in the 'Summary tables June 2006 to June 2015' at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-bulletin-june-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-bulletin-june-2015</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-15T11:36:53.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443772/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443772/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many recorded attacks there were against prison officers in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","21996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443773","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-15","<p>The national statistics on safety in custody use the category of self-harm incidents, defined as “any act where a prisoner deliberately harms themselves irrespective of the method, intent or severity of any injury”. They do not include a separate category of “attempted suicide”, because the intent of the prisoner is often unknown. Some incidents are more likely to result in a fatality than others, but the point at which a self-harm incident becomes an attempted suicide is unclear.</p><br /><p>Summary statistics on self-harm in prison custody are published quarterly, and the latest annual figures, for the ten years to June 2015, can be found in Table 3 of the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/472712/Safety-in-custody-summary-q2-2015.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/472712/Safety-in-custody-summary-q2-2015.xls</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-15T11:47:01.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443773/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443773/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Prisons: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents of attempted suicide there were in prisons in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","21997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443774","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-15","<p>Every death in custody is a tragedy and we are committed to reducing the number of deaths in prisons.</p><br /><p>Summary statistics on deaths in prison custody by apparent cause are published quarterly, and the latest annual figures, for the ten years to September 2015, can be found in Table 2 of the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/472712/Safety-in-custody-summary-q2-2015.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/472712/Safety-in-custody-summary-q2-2015.xls</a></p><br /><p>This includes the number of deaths in the category of homicide, defined as any death of a prisoner at the hands of another.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-15T11:51:30.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443774/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443774/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many deaths in prisons were caused by attacks by other prisoners in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","21798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443775","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-21","<p>All prison officers receive training on mental health issues as part of their initial training course. The majority of mental health training is delivered locally and costs attributed to such training are not held centrally.</p><p>The national NOMS Learning and Development department have spent the following in the last three years (staff and sundry costs only) training prison officers to help prisoners with mental health issues:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><strong>2013 £k</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014 £k</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015 £k</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Mental Health Training</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>77</p></td><td><p>84</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /> <br /><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-21T16:12:31.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443775/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443775/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-11","Prison Officers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department spent on training prison officers to help prisoners with mental health issues in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","21799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443776","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-18","<p>In addition to the National Army Museum, in the current financial year the Ministry of Defence (MOD) supported 69 regimental and corps museums across the UK through a combination of a £1.3 million total grant in aid, £1.6 million salary costs, and providing utilities and some support running costs when a museum is located on a MOD site. Funding beyond the current financial year will be set later this year, and will be subject to the normal review process.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-01-18T16:00:04.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443776/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443776/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-11","Armed Forces: Museums and Galleries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has for funding by his Department of regimental museums over the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Sir Jeffrey M. Donaldson","Lagan Valley","Mr Jeffrey M. Donaldson","21736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443777","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<br /><p>The majority of Reserve personnel train on a regular basis, effectively balancing their commitment to their Service with the competing demands of a busy modern life. The Ministry of Defence recognises and rewards reservists' commitment to our nation in various ways.</p><p>We have provided better equipment, and more opportunities for interesting and challenging experiences, including exercises, adventurous training and overseas training.</p><p>Volunteer reservists are paid for attendance at training and also receive a tax-exempt training bounty provided they fulfil their Service's annual training requirement including a two week camp or course. They have also received an annual paid leave entitlement since 1 April 2013.</p><p>In addition, since April 2015, reservists have been eligible for the new Armed Forces Pension Scheme for non-mobilised service, based on paid attendance.</p><p>These are just some examples of the actions the Department has taken to demonstrate that reservists are valued and valuable.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-01-14T16:15:00.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443777/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443777/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-11","Reserve Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to improve the attendance of reservists at weekly drills, training exercises and medical assessments.","false","Biography information for Sir Jeffrey M. Donaldson","Lagan Valley","Mr Jeffrey M. Donaldson","21901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443778","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-14","<p>One of the Northern Ireland Office’s objectives for the commemoration of the decade of centenaries of 1912-1922 is to work with the Irish Government to promote greater understanding of our shared history and promote reconciliation.</p><p>2016 will mark the centenary of a number of significant events including the Easter Rising, the Battle of the Somme and the Battle of Jutland. The Northern Ireland Office is working with colleagues in DCMS and others to prepare for a number of these commemorations. All invitations received are being considered on a case by case basis.</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-14T12:06:10.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443778/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443778/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-11","Anniversaries: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what plans she has to participate in events to commemorate the centenary of the (a) Easter Rising and (b) Battle of the Somme.","false","Biography information for Sir Jeffrey M. Donaldson","Lagan Valley","Mr Jeffrey M. Donaldson","21902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443779","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-18","<p>Statistics showing the number of English applicants awarded maintenance grants are published annually by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the Statistical First Release ‘<em>Student Support for Higher Education in England</em>’.</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx</a></p><br /><p>Data provided by the SLC indicates there were 33,700 English applicants awarded maintenance grants for HE courses associated with publicly-funded further education colleges in the academic year 2014/15.</p><p><em></em></p><p>A course can be held at a campus of the associated institution or at a franchise location, therefore numbers of applicants to courses associated with an institution may not necessarily reflect the numbers studying at the institution. An awarded applicant will only receive payments once SLC have received confirmation from the applicant’s provider that the student has been registered on the course.</p><br /> <br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-18T17:48:54.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443779/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443779/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-11","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many students studying higher education in further education colleges received maintenance grants in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","21886"
